{"key":"processedPost-12630966","value":{"id":12630966,"first":12630304,"last":12631563,"when":1274886844,"utime":"05/26/10 06:14 PM","content":"Corn should be considered an avenue of last resort if you absolutely can't find rye berries.&nbsp; Corn is full of bacterial endospores that are able to withstand even 2 hours in a pressure cooker.&nbsp; Your rate of failure will be much higher with corn.&nbsp; Not every grow will fail, but the <i>rate of failure</i> will be higher.&nbsp; <br /><br />There's a reason commercial mushroom farms use rye berries.&nbsp; They have to sell their product for $3 to $4 per pound wholesale, so any higher than normal rate of contamination or poor performance means the difference between making a profit and going broke.<br />RR","title":"Re: Corn or rye?"}}